{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Finding\n\n`src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/verify.py`'s `verify_findings()` is the shared Pass-2 kernel\nentry point that chunks findings, runs each chunk via an injected `run_chunk` LLM callable, and\ntallies `outcome_counts` (`clean`/`recovered`/`empty_outcomes`/`unrecoverable`) plus\n`contract_violations`. It is fully implemented and unit-tested\n(`tests/unit/test_review_kernel.py`, `tests/unit/test_review_kernel_rules.py`), but neither live\nconsumer pipeline calls it, and â€” per plan-review feedback on an earlier draft of this ticket â€”\nneither CAN call it as-is: both pipelines run their Pass-2 model call as a declarative workflow\nprompt step (one YAML step per token-budgeted chunk, merged by the executor), not as a\nprocedural loop with a `run_chunk` callback in scope. `verify_findings()`'s per-chunk\n`outcome_counts` tally (which chunk was clean vs empty vs a `StructuredOutputError`) depends on\nbeing IN that per-chunk loop; by the time `plan_review_decide`/`code_review_decide` see the\ninput, the workflow engine has already merged every chunk's output into one flat\n`verifications` list, and per-chunk boundaries (which chunk contributed what) are gone. So\n`empty_outcomes`/`unrecoverable` (chunk-level execution signals) are **not reconstructable** at\nthe `*_decide` step boundary without a separate architecture change (the verify prompt step\nitself emitting per-chunk metadata as a named workflow output before the merge) â€” that is\nexplicitly deferred as follow-on work, not this ticket's scope.\n\nWhat IS shared today, and inconsistently, between the two pipelines:\n\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/workflow_ops.py`'s `plan_review_decide` (~line 425) calls\n  `review_kernel.reshape_verifications(...)` on the merged `verifications` list, and on\n  `reshape.has_violations` (malformed/duplicate/unexpected indices) calls\n  `orchestrator.record_contract_violation(reshape.summary())` â€” a run-scoped ContextVar sink\n  (`plan_review/orchestrator.py:321-357`: `collect_contract_violations`/\n  `record_contract_violation`/`drain_contract_violations`) activated in\n  `gate_dispatch.produce_plan_review_verdict` (~line 171) and drained into\n  `coverage[\"verification_contract_violations\"]` in `plan_review_coach` (~line 563).\n- `src/rebar/llm/code_review/workflow_ops.py`'s `code_review_decide` (~line 395) does the exact\n  same `reshape_verifications(...)` call and `has_violations` check, but only\n  `logger.error(...)`s â€” no sink exists for code-review, so the violation data never reaches\n  `finalize_code_review_verdict`'s coverage, and there is no `outcome_counts` telemetry there at\n  all.\n\n## Scope note\n\n`c2c5-53a7-2ce0-4d98` is a child of epic `6eca-183e-1cd2-4fb9` (Janitor Cleanup 2026-07-19),\ndiscovered mid-run (`discovered_from` -> `1aa8-cdde-4ff6-40d0`) after the epic's other 5 leaves\nhad already been decomposed and were not in the epic's original plan/file_impact. It was left\nopen and unworked when the other 5 leaves closed, per an explicit scoping decision recorded on\nthe epic. It is now being completed under direct operator instruction (\"Complete this story\"),\nwhich supersedes that earlier deferral.\n\n## Remediation\n\nTwo concrete, single-path changes (no `run_chunk`/`verify_findings()` involvement â€” that\nkernel entry point stays reserved for callers that own the procedural chunk loop, e.g. a\nfuture non-workflow consumer):\n\n1. **Shared contract-violation sink.** Move the existing ContextVar-backed sink\n   (`collect_contract_violations`/`record_contract_violation`/`drain_contract_violations`,\n   currently private to `plan_review/orchestrator.py`) into `review_kernel` (e.g.\n   `review_kernel/verify.py` or a new `review_kernel/telemetry.py`) as the ONE implementation\n   both pipelines import â€” not a duplicate. Update `plan_review/orchestrator.py`'s and\n   `plan_review/workflow_ops.py`'s existing call sites to import it from its new home (a\n   mechanical rename, no behavior change for plan-review). Wire the equivalent into\n   `code_review`: activate `collect_contract_violations()` around the workflow run in\n   `gate_dispatch._run_code_review_gate` (mirroring `produce_plan_review_verdict`'s\n   `with assemble_context_cache(), collect_contract_violations(), gate_config(cfg):`), call\n   `record_contract_violation(reshape.summary())` in `code_review_decide` when\n   `reshape.has_violations` (replacing the bare `logger.error`, keeping the log too), and drain\n   it into `finalize_code_review_verdict`'s verdict coverage as\n   `coverage[\"verification_contract_violations\"]`, mirroring plan-review's\n   `coverage[\"verification_contract_violations\"]` write in `plan_review_coach`.\n\n2. **`outcome_counts` at the `*_decide` boundary (whole-run tally, not per-chunk).** Add a\n   small shared helper in `review_kernel` â€” e.g.\n   `decide_outcome_counts(raw_verifs: list, findings: list, reshape: VerificationReshape) ->\n   dict[str, int]` â€” that derives a single-run `{\"clean\": int, \"recovered\": int,\n   \"empty_outcomes\": int, \"unrecoverable\": int}` from data already available at the merged\n   `*_decide` boundary:\n   - `empty_outcomes = 1` if `findings` is non-empty but `raw_verifs` came back completely\n     empty, else `0`.\n   - `unrecoverable` is **always `0`** in this leaf â€” a `StructuredOutputError` inside one\n     chunk is swallowed by the workflow engine's own repair/retry layer before the merged\n     output ever reaches `*_decide`; a total verify-step failure already surfaces via the\n     existing `coverage[\"verify_failed\"]` signal (ticket 59bc/b24d), which this ticket does not\n     touch. Tracking true per-chunk `unrecoverable` counts requires the verify prompt step\n     itself to emit per-chunk metadata as a named workflow output before the merge â€” an\n     explicitly deferred follow-on, not this ticket.\n   - Otherwise (findings present and at least one verification came back):\n     `recovered = 1, clean = 0` if `reshape.has_violations` (some entries were malformed/\n     duplicate/unexpected but the run still produced usable verifications), else\n     `clean = 1, recovered = 0`.\n   Call this helper from both `plan_review_decide` and `code_review_decide` and add\n   `outcome_counts` to each step's output dict (additive â€” no existing output key removed).\n   Thread it into each pipeline's verdict coverage the same way `hierarchy_incomplete` was\n   threaded in ticket b24d: `coverage[\"outcome_counts\"]` set by `*_decide`'s output. No\n   downstream INDETERMINATE/PASS logic changes â€” this is additive observability, exactly like\n   the drop-in for `verification_contract_violations` above.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `plan_review_decide` and `code_review_decide` both emit an `outcome_counts` field (a\n      single-run `{clean, recovered, empty_outcomes, unrecoverable}` tally, `unrecoverable`\n      always `0` per the documented boundary limitation above) computed by ONE shared\n      `review_kernel` helper â€” no duplicated tallying logic between the two pipelines.\n- [ ] `code_review_decide` records contract violations via the SAME shared\n      `collect_contract_violations`/`record_contract_violation`/`drain_contract_violations`\n      sink `plan_review_decide` uses (moved into `review_kernel`), activated in\n      `gate_dispatch._run_code_review_gate` and drained into\n      `finalize_code_review_verdict`'s `coverage[\"verification_contract_violations\"]`.\n- [ ] Existing plan-review and code-review test suites continue to pass unmodified (the sink\n      move is a mechanical relocation â€” plan-review's behavior is byte-identical); new tests\n      cover code-review's `outcome_counts`/contract-violation propagation specifically, and at\n      least one test covers the moved sink from its new shared location for both pipelines.\n- [ ] No change to either pipeline's decision thresholds, impact functions, or verdict shape\n      (`outcome_counts` and `verification_contract_violations` are additive coverage keys only).\n\n## Verify commands\n\n- `pytest tests/unit/test_review_kernel.py tests/unit/test_review_kernel_rules.py -q`\n- `pytest tests/unit/plan_review -q`\n- `pytest tests/unit/code_review -q`\n- `pytest tests -q`\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784743762649388001,"uuid":"ca18553c-f9b4-4648-bc9a-4c99a819d32c"}